i## Purchasing A New Optimus MUXed Laptop		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIf you are interested in GPU passthrough and are looking for a new		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ilaptop, you can refer to my guidelines.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe prerequisites for laptop GPU passthrough is:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. The NVIDIA GPU itself must be capable of video output		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. There is at least one video output directly connected to that GPU		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, it's extremely rare for a laptop manufacturer to mention the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iport connection schemes on their product pages, so we have to infer		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifrom more common specifications:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Prefer a laptop with a MUX switch, aka ones that can switch their		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   internal screen onto the dedicated GPU. In this case, the dedicated		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   GPU must be capable of video output, and there's a high chance that		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   the manufacturer connected the chassis video outputs to the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   dedicated GPU:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Common examples are: 2020 and 2021 Lenovo Legion series, HP OMEN		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     series, and Dell G15.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - **I do not guarantee that this list is accurate!** Do your own		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     research or ask a sales agent to make sure.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Or choose a laptop with a mid-range to high-end graphics card. For		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   NVIDIA GPUs the model number needs to end with 60 or larger.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - It's common for mid to top-tier NVIDIA GPUs to have video output		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     functionality, and the manufacturer is likely to connect chassis		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     video ports to them.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Do not purchase a laptop with a GPU that ends in 50 or lower,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     like an RTX 3050 or GTX 1650 Ti. They very likely don't support		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     video output.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. Take advantage of unconditional return policies.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - Since manufacturers won't advertise or won't even care much about		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     their video output connections, we have to guess from the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     specifications and advertising pages. Therefore, it's possible		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     that you followed every rule above yet got a laptop that doesn't		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     support GPU passthrough. In this case, you may consider returning		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     or reselling it.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   - In some countries, laptop manufacturers will only accept an		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     unconditional return if the preinstalled Windows and Office are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     never activated online. However, the latest Windows 11 requires		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     you to activate online in its first-boot setup wizard. You may		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     consider trying GPU passthrough with a Linux installation on your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     USB drive before activating Windows.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## About Intel GVT-g Virtual GPUs		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i5th to 9th-Gen Intel integrated graphics support virtualizing the GPU		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iitself, or in other words, splitting it into several virtual GPUs. The		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ivirtual GPUs can be passed through into VMs so they get GPU		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iacceleration, while the host can still display stuff on the very same		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iGPU.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHowever, the GVT-g driver in Linux doesn't support 10th-Gen or newer		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIntel CPUs, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hIntel has no plan to support them	URL:https://github.com/intel/gvt-linux/issues/126	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i. In addition, the GVT-g virtual GPU cannot form an Optimus		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iconfiguration with an NVIDIA GPU, so it isn't useful anyway.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThat's why we're ignoring GVT-g and focusing on the NVIDIA GPU in this		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iguide.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## (2023-05) About Intel SR-IOV Virtual GPUs		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i11th-Gen and later Intel integrated graphics support another form of		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ivirtualization: SR-IOV. Intel has		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hofficially released the source code to the kernel module with SR-IOV	URL:https://github.com/intel/linux-intel-lts/tree/lts-v5.15.49-adl-linux-220826T092047Z/drivers/gpu/drm/i915	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i, but it isn't merged into Linux mainline as of now.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hThere's a third party project that ports the code into a DKMS module	URL:https://github.com/strongtz/i915-sriov-dkms	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i, but success rate is not high according to reports in Issues section.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iI tried it with my i7-11800H and didn't succeed. Therefore, this time		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwe will not try SR-IOV on Intel GPUs.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
