i# Steps		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i## Stop Host OS from Tampering with NVIDIA GPU		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> Most of the content is the same as		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
1> my post in 2021	/en/article/modify-computer/laptop-intel-nvidia-optimus-passthrough.lantian/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> .		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe NVIDIA driver on the Host OS will hold control of the dGPU, and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istop VM from using it. Therefore you need to replace the driver with `vfio-pci` ,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibuilt solely for PCIe passthrough.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iHere are the steps for disabling the NVIDIA driver and passing control		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ito the PCIe passthrough module:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Run `lspci -nn | grep NVIDIA` and obtain an output similar to:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     0000:01:00.0 VGA compatible controller [0300]: NVIDIA Corporation GA104M [GeForce RTX 3070 Mobile / Max-Q] [10de:249d] (rev a1)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     0000:01:00.1 Audio device [0403]: NVIDIA Corporation GA104 High Definition Audio Controller [10de:228b] (rev a1)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Here `[10de:249d]` is the vendor ID and device ID of the dGPU,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   where `10de` means this device is manufactured by NVIDIA, and `249d`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   means this is a RTX 3070. `228b` is the audio output on the HDMI		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   port, which should also be taken over by `vfio-pci` .		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Create `/etc/modprobe.d/lantian.conf` with the following content:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     options vfio-pci ids=10de:249d,10de:228b		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   This configures `vfio-pci` , the kernel module responsible for PCIe		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   passthrough, to manage the dGPU. `ids` is the vendor ID and device		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   ID of the device to be passed through.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. Modify `/etc/mkinitcpio.conf` , add the following contents to `MODULES` :		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     MODULES=(vfio_pci vfio vfio_iommu_type1 vfio_virqfd)		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   And remove anything related to NVIDIA drivers (such as `nvidia` ),		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   or make sure they're listed after VFIO drivers. Now PCIe		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   passthrough module will take control of the dGPU in the early		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   booting process, preventing NVIDIA drivers from taking control.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i4. Run `mkinitcpio -P` to update the initramfs.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i5. Reboot.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i(2023-05) If you're using NixOS, you can use the following config:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  {		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    boot.kernelModules = ["vfio-pci"];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    boot.extraModprobeConfig = ''		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      # Change to your GPU's vendor ID and device ID		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i      options vfio-pci ids=10de:249d		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    '';		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i    boot.blacklistedKernelModules = ["nouveau" "nvidiafb" "nvidia" "nvidia-uvm" "nvidia-drm" "nvidia-modeset"];		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i  }		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
