i## Passthrough Keyboard & Mouse Operations		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe latest Looking Glass can relay keyboard and mouse events reliably		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
inow. These steps are kept for reference only.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe relay of the keyboard and mouse in Looking Glass isn't very		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istable, as misses of operation can happen from time to time.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iTherefore, if you want to play some games in the VM, you need a more		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ireliable way to pass your keyboard and mouse into the VM.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWe have two options: letting Libvirt capture the keyboard and mouse		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ievents or simply pass your keyboard and mouse into the VM.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Capturing Keyboard and Mouse Events.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   On Linux, all keyboard and mouse operations are passed to the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   desktop environment via the `evdev` (or `Event Device` ) framework.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Libvirt can capture your operations and pass them to the VM. In		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   addition, Libvirt can switch the control between the host and the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   VM whenever you press Left Ctrl and the Right Ctrl, so you can		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   operate on both the host and the VM with one keyboard-mouse combo.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   First run `ls -l /dev/input/by-path` on the host to see your		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   present `evdev` devices. I have these ones for example:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     pci-0000:00:14.0-usb-0:1:1.1-event-mouse               # USB mouse		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     pci-0000:00:14.0-usb-0:1:1.1-mouse		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     pci-0000:00:14.0-usb-0:6:1.0-event		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     pci-0000:00:15.0-platform-i2c_designware.0-event-mouse # Builtin Touchpad		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     pci-0000:00:15.0-platform-i2c_designware.0-mouse		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     pci-0000:00:1f.3-platform-skl_hda_dsp_generic-event		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     platform-i8042-serio-0-event-kbd                       # Builtin Keyboard		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     platform-pcspkr-event-spkr		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Those with `event-mouse` are mouses, and the `event-kbd` ones are		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   keyboards.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Then, run `virsh edit Windows` to edit the VM config. Add these		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   into the `<devices>` section:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     <input type="evdev">		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       <!-- Change the mouse or keyboard path based on your ls result -->		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       <source dev="/dev/input/by-path/platform-i8042-serio-0-event-kbd" grab="all" repeat="on"/>		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     </input>		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     <!-- Repeat if you have many mouses or keyboards -->		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     <input type="evdev">		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i       <source dev="/dev/input/by-path/pci-0000:00:15.0-platform-i2c_designware.0-event-mouse" grab="all" repeat="on"/>		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     </input>		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
