i## Accelerating Looking Glass with Kernel Modules		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> Most of the content in this section is from		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
h> https://looking-glass.io/docs/B6/module/	URL:https://looking-glass.io/docs/B6/module/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iLooking Glass provides a kernel module for the IVSHMEM shared memory		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idevice. It allows Looking Glass to read the display output efficiently		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwith DMA to improve the framerate.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. Install Linux kernel header files and DKMS, or the packages of `linux-headers`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   and `dkms` on Arch Linux.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. Install `looking-glass-module-dkms` from AUR.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. Set up an Udev rule: create `/etc/udev/rules.d/99-kvmfr.rules` with		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   the following content:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     SUBSYSTEM=="kvmfr", OWNER="lantian", GROUP="kvm", MODE="0660"		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Replace `lantian` with your own username.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i4. Configure the memory size: create `/etc/modprobe.d/looking-glass.conf`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   with the following content:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     # The memory size is calculates in the same way as VM's shmem.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     options kvmfr static_size_mb=64		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i5. Load the module automatically on boot: create `/etc/modules-load.d/looking-glass.conf`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   with a single line of `kvmfr` .		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i6. Run `sudo modprobe kvmfr` to load the module. Now a `kvmfr0` device		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   should appear under `/dev` , and this is the memory device for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   Looking Glass.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i7. Edit `/etc/apparmor.d/local/abstractions/libvirt-qemu` and add this		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   line:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i     /dev/kvmfr0 rw,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   It allows the VM to access the device. Run `sudo systemctl restart		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   apparmor` to restart AppArmor.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i8. Run `virsh edit Windows` to change the VM's configuration：		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   1. Delete `<shmem>` section from `<devices>` :		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i        <shmem name='looking-glass'>		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
