i## Cutting Power to GPU When Unused		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i**2022-01-26 Update: testing shows that the NVIDIA GPU still isn't		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
icompletely shut down after applying the patch. The power draw is the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isame as before. This section is now invalid.**		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> This section only applies to 20-series of NVIDIA GPUs or newer. They		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> can shut themselves down with the NVIDIA official drivers. The		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> 10-series or older GPUs don't support this feature.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> 		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> This section involves compiling a kernel yourself, and **using an		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> patch without extensive inspection or testing** . Not intended for		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i> novice users. Evaluate the risks yourself.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWhen you aren't using the VM, the `vfio-pci` driver in charge of PCIe		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipassthrough sets the device to the `D3` mode, aka the power saving		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imode of PCIe devices. But there are two types of `D3` modes: `D3hot` ,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iwhere the device is still powered, and `D3cold` , where the device is		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ishut off completely. Currently, the `vfio-pci` driver in the kernel		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ionly supports `D3hot` , and the NVIDIA GPU will still consume around		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i10 watts of power since its chip power isn't cut. This impacts the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ibattery life of laptops.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iAn NVIDIA engineer posted a patchset for `vfio-pci` 's `D3cold`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isupport on the Linux kernel mailing list. With this patchset, the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iNVIDIA GPU will be shut down completely when the VM is off. It saves		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ipower for your battery.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iThe patchset can be found at		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://lore.kernel.org/lkml/20211115133640.2231-1-abhsahu@nvidia.com/T/	URL:https://lore.kernel.org/lkml/20211115133640.2231-1-abhsahu@nvidia.com/T/	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i, which consists of three patches. I combined the three patches and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iuploaded the result to		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://github.com/xddxdd/pkgbuild/blob/master/linux-xanmod-lantian/0007-vfio-pci-d3cold.patch	URL:https://github.com/xddxdd/pkgbuild/blob/master/linux-xanmod-lantian/0007-vfio-pci-d3cold.patch	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iPatching kernel is relatively simple for Arch Linux. Most kernel		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iPKGBUILDs in AUR can apply patches automatically. All you have to do		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iis to download the PKGBUILD for a kernel and add the patch to its `source`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
isection. See my commit for an example:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
hhttps://github.com/xddxdd/pkgbuild/commit/406adb7bf5657cfe07bb17ff561d11ed97ebab39	URL:https://github.com/xddxdd/pkgbuild/commit/406adb7bf5657cfe07bb17ff561d11ed97ebab39	{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i**DO NOTE that this patch doesn't guarantee stability.**		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iBased on mailing list discussions:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. It's an RFC patch, aka a testing patch. There is a big `[RFC]` on		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   the title of the e-mails.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. If the GPU driver in the VM ever attempts to switch the GPU to `D3cold`		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   mode, with this patch, there are risks of resetting the GPU, losing		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   all states, and crashing the VM. Although I have never encountered		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   such problems in my experience, you should be aware of the possible		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   outcomes.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. The developer only tested some GPUs from NVIDIA. It does not		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   guarantee support for other PCIe devices.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i**Use this at your own risk.**		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
